Rating: 4
I made this cake two ways-- with 1 cup oil and 1/2 cup buttermilk (instead of 1.5 cups oil) and still way to oily. the reverse proportion worked beautifully and is what i'll use from now on, i.e., 1/2 cup oil, and 1 cup reduced fat buttermilk. i can't figure out why the recipe requires all the oil-- i think the feel and texture of the cake suffers rather than benefits from it. i also reduced the sugar by 25% in the cake and by 50% in the frosting-- much better. the vanilla in the frosting is overkill in my opinion as well, and would be better substituted with another liquid (i used milk) to keep the consistency. garnished with blackbberries and pecans for an impressive presentation. I also ground 3/4 cup of pecans fairly fine to add to the batter, and got a really gorgeous light crumb with a bit of extra texture. there are many achingly sweet desserts out there, and i think one of the great things about carrot cake is that it's an earthy dessert that can seem almost virtuous while still being fantastically delicious. this is a really great recipe with the modifications. my search is over.

